ere (teamwork), positive crew atmosphere. Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork), egocentric, not willing to further education (professional development). Technical competence? Not explicit but decision making suggests cognitive. Weather? Not given.\n\nD: strengths: responds adequately to unexpected events (some decision), concentrates well, solves problems extremely well (technical), takes responsibility seriously (reliability). Weaknesses: arrogant, weak leadership, possibly poor teamwork (loner). Decision speed? Not explicit. Under pressure? Not known.\n\nWe need to weigh. Likely best candidate is C because of reliability, quick correct decisions, positive crew atmosphere, despite communication difficulty and egocentric. B also strong but teamwork issues. A has leadership but unorganized. D has problem solving but weak leadership and arrogance.\n\nWe might ask other agents for missing info: e.g., ask about Candidate C's technical competence (weather assessment, computer skills) or about Candidate B's decision-making speed. Also ask about Candidate D's decision-making speed under pressure (already asked, no info). Maybe ask about Candidate D's teamwork/communication (already asked). Could ask about Candidate A's stress handling (not asked). Also ask about Candidate C's willingness to professional development (already known not willing). Could ask about Candidate B's leadership qualities.\n\nWe need to produce public message: summarize evaluation, note gaps, maybe ask targeted question to fill gaps before final vote. Since we have enough to make a tentative preference, but we should still ask for missing info that could change view, e.g., Candidate B's teamwork, but we have grumpy/uncooperative. Maybe ask about Candidate C's ability to handle stress (not given). Also ask about Candidate A's stress handling.\n\nThus public message: present evaluation, note missing info, ask other agents: \"Do you have any info on Candidate A's ability to handle stress